ivided into three parts dealing with expectations, experiences and explanations of bombing, this book considers the child's view of wartime violence, analysing resilience, understanding and trauma. It contributes significantly to scholarship on civilian life in Occupied France, and will appeal to students, academics and general readers interested in the history of Vichy France, oral history and the experiences of children in war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBombing, AerialzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCampaignszFrance. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xChildrenzFrance. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2020. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aAllied bombing.  aAllied propaganda.  aBoulogne-Billancourt.  aBrest.  aFrance.  aFrench children.  aFrench collective memory.  aLille.  aSecond World War.  aVichy.  achildren's agency.  achildren's wartime lives.  aemotional responses.  aevacuees.  amunicipal-level preparations.  aoral history.  apublic death.  arefugees.  asensory response.  awar preparedness.1 aDodd, Lindsey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499741040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997410423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997410/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles